# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-holt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Historically a part of Lancashire, Aigburth is mainly residential and covers an area following Aigburth Road (A561) and the areas either side of it until it reaches Garston.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The suburb is to the south of Sefton Park and adjoins Otterspool Park, which leads to Otterspool Promenade on the Mersey.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Housing in the district is mostly a mixture of terraced and semi detached homes, with large detached houses (mostly converted into flats or hotels) in Aigburth Drive overlooking Sefton Park and modern estates containing detached and semi detached houses in the Riverside Drive area.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Lark Lane (between Aigburth Road and Sefton Park) is a lively place with many independent shops, restaurants and bars.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] *The Guardian* published an article about Aigburth in 2007 in its 'Let's move to ...' series.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Beorg or berg is more usually rendered *-borough* (as in Barlborough in Derbyshire) or more rarely as *-barrow* (as in Backbarrow in Cumbria).
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The name was also recorded as *Eikberei* in an undated record.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] A possible other meaning of Aigburth is Aiges' Berth, meaning the place where the Viking Aiges berthed his long boat.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] This is plausible because Aigburth is right on the Merseyside river mouth and not on a hill.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The nearby hill has a Viking name Toxteth, which means the camp of Toces.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The spelling *Aigburgh* (or, more rarely, *Aighburgh*) is sometimes found in old publications and historical documents (for example, S.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Lewis, *A Topographical Dictionary of England* (1848)), as well as in modern references to former residents and is occasionally seen as an alternative (if incorrect) spelling today.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The area was previously part of the Mossley Hill parliamentary constituency and, as such, returned David Alton (now Lord Alton of Liverpool) for many years.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] It is now part of the Liverpool Riverside constituency and returned Louise Ellman as MP in the 2005 and 2010 general elections.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The area is covered by the Liverpool City Council wards of Aigburth and Mossley Hill.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The current councillors are Paul Ruddick and Rob McAllister-Bell.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The Aigburth Park halls of residence of Liverpool Hope University are located close to the railway line on St Michael's Road.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Up towards Mossley Hill are the former University of Liverpool Carnatic Halls of Residence built in between Elmswood and Carnatic Roads.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] These are closed, pending redevelopment.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] On the piece of land between Mossley Hill Road and Barkhill Road is the IM Marsh Campus of Liverpool John Moores University, where the Faculty of Education, Health and Community is based.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Secondary schools in Aigburth include St Margaret's Church of England Academy and Auckland College, a private school for ages 5–18.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] State primary schools in Aigburth are Sudley Infants and Sudley Juniors as well as St Michael-in-the-Hamlet Primary.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] Prior to the reorganisation of secondary education in Liverpool in the 1980s, Aigburth was also home to Aigburth Vale Comprehensive School for Girls, formerly Aigburth Vale High School for Girls, which merged with Quarry Bank School to form Calderstones School.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] The area is served by Aigburth railway station on the Northern Line of the Merseyrail network, located some distance from larger residential areas.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] St Michaels railway station is also situated in the area, at the bottom of Southwood Road.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] South Liverpool F.C., Liverpool Cricket Club, a regular home venue of Lancashire County Cricket Club, and Sefton Park Cricket Club, are located in Aigburth.
[src:alfred-holt/aigburth] St Margaret's Cricket and Community Sports Centre houses Respect 4 All, an official charity of Liverpool Football Club offering free football sports coaching for disabled people.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt was one of six brothers, born to George Holt and his wife, Emma.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] In 1866, he and his brother, Philip Holt founded the Alfred Holt and Company and the Ocean Steam Ship Company, which owned and operated the majority of the company's vessels.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt & Co later became Blue Funnel Line.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] One of his other brothers, George Holt, was also a noted Liverpool merchant and ship owner.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] His youngest brother, Robert Durning Holt, was Mayor of Liverpool.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Holt served an apprenticeship under the chief engineer of the Liverpool & Manchester Railway, learning the basics of both mechanical and civil engineering.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] On finishing his apprenticeship, he established himself as an engineering consultant, and soon became involved in ship management.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The efficiencies of compound steam engines, which were widely used in railway locomotives, were not available to steamships as the Board of trade limited the steam pressures of marine boilers to about 20 psi (140 kPa).
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Not only did Holt understand the well-known benefits of higher steam pressures running compound engines, but he also had the negotiating skills to gain the approval of the Board of Trade to put this into effect.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The result was *Cleator*, the testbed for these ideas, running at 60 psi (410 kPa).
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Holt then set about designing a steamship for the China trade.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] This was a route worked almost entirely by sail.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company had a steamship route to China from Britain that went along the Mediterranean, with an overland section to the north end of the Red Sea and then to China by sea.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] A few auxiliary steamships sailed to China round the Cape of Good Hope, using their steam engines in light winds.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The more prominent cargo vessels on this route were the clippers engaged in the tea trade, but many ordinary merchant sailing vessels also sailed to China.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The passage from London to China is about 14,000 nautical miles.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The problem for a steamer was to have space for enough coal for this distance, but still carry a commercial amount of cargo.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] Holt achieved a big increase in efficiency that made this possible.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] He married his first wife, Catherine Long in 1865.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] They had a daughter, Jane (1867–1922), who married the marine biologist William Abbott Herdman; a son, George, who became one of the managers of the Blue Funnel Line; and another son, who died in his teens.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] After Catherine's death in 1869, Alfred Holt married her cousin, Frances Long (in 1871), with whom he had two more sons.
[src:alfred-holt/alfred-holt] The youngest son, also named Alfred (1877–1931), became a Reader in Chemistry at the University of Liverpool.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Alfred Holt founded the business on 16 January 1866.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The main operating subsidiary was the Ocean Steam Ship Company, which owned and operated the majority of the company's vessels.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] A Dutch subsidiary, the **Nederlandsche Stoomvaart Maatschappij Oceaan**, was founded in 1891, as was the **East India Ocean Steam Ship Company**, operated from Singapore.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] This latter was sold in 1899 to Norddeutscher Lloyd.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The company acquired the competing **China Mutual Steam Navigation Company** in 1902, keeping it as a subsidiary company but operating it as part of Blue Funnel Line.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The company's ships connected the major ports of Shanghai and Hong Kong to Liverpool.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The ship's crews were Chinese as well as European.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] As a consequence, some Chinese seamen settled in Liverpool from the 1860s to found the oldest Chinese community in Europe.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Ships of the Blue Funnel fleet all had names from classical Greek legend or history.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The majority were cargo ships, but most of the Ocean SS Co cargo ships also had capacity for a few passengers.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The line also had a small number of purely passenger vessels.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] In the 1920s, Blue Funnel became the first British shipping company to employ a woman marine engineer.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] These were two of the first new ships built for Blue Funnel to replace its Second World War losses.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The company expanded in 1937 through acquisition of the Glen Line in 1935, that provided cargo and passenger service to the Far East from eastern English ports such as London.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Wurtzburg, brought Herbert Gladstone McDavid to London from the company's Liverpool office as director of the new acquisition and profits increased.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Eight new Glenearn class ships were ordered, four from UK shipyards and four from abroad but not all were delivered when the Second World War started.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The first Outward Bound school was opened in Aberdyfi, Wales in 1941 with the support of the Blue Funnel Line.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Outward Bound's founding mission was to improve the survival chances of young seamen after their ships were torpedoed in the mid-Atlantic.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Captain JF "Freddy" Fuller of the Blue Funnel Line took over the leadership of the Aberdyfi school in 1942 and served the Outward Bound movement as senior warden until 1971.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Fuller was seconded following wartime experience during the Battle of the Atlantic of surviving two successive U-boat attacks and commanding an open lifeboat in the Atlantic Ocean for 35 days without losing a single member of the crew.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Blue Funnel lost 16 ships in the First World War and 30 in the Second.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] After each war it restored its fleet with new ships.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] After the Second War it regained tonnage rapidly by buying six Victory ships from the United States Maritime Commission in 1946 and eight *"Sam-"* ships from the Ministry of War Transport in 1947.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Six of the eight new ships ordered by Glen Line in 1938 were reacquired, resulting in a fleet of 15 ships by September 1948.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The twice-monthly fast service and a slower secondary service to the Far East resumed.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Two Blue Funnel ships, *Agapenor* and *Melampus* were trapped by the Six-Day War of 1967 and became part of the Yellow Fleet in the Great Bitter Lake, remaining there until 1975.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] From 1947 to 1970, as Britain's empire began to shrink, so did its trade.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Simultaneously, companies from other parts of the world began to operate more competitively.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Cabotage regulations prevented British flag companies from trading on routes that were previously their monopolies.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Several factors resulted in a decreased number in the Blue Funnel's fleet.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] Among the more notable of officers to work at Blue Funnel line was Richard Woodman who began his seagoing career as an apprentice with the line in 1960.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The company finally came to an end in 1988 when Ocean Group withdrew from the Barber Blue Sea Service, its last shipping line.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The Merseyside Maritime Museum Archive and Library holds the company archive.
[src:alfred-holt/blue-funnel-line] The company's seafarers later went to fill various roles in the British maritime shore based establishment, including Malcolm Maclachlan, a lecturer in Glasgow and a popular author of books on maritime business.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The **Board of Trade** is a British government body concerned with commerce and industry, currently within the Department for Business and Trade.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board has gone through several evolutions, beginning with extensive involvement in colonial matters in the 17th century, to powerful regulatory functions in the Victorian Era and early 20th century.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] It was virtually dormant in the last third of the 20th century.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In 2017, it was revitalised as an advisory board headed by the International Trade Secretary who has nominally held the title of President of the Board of Trade, and who at present is the only privy counsellor of the board, the other members of the present board filling roles as advisors.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board was first established as a temporary committee of England's Privy Council to advise on colonial (plantation) questions in the early 17th century, when these settlements were initially forming.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Between 1696 and 1782 the Board of Trade, in partnership with the various secretaries of state over that time, held responsibility for colonial affairs, particularly in British America.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The newly created office of Home Secretary then held colonial responsibility until 1801, when the Secretary of State for War and the Colonies was established.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Following the loss of the American War of Independence, both the board and the short-lived secretaryship were dismissed by the king on 2 May 1782 and the board was abolished later by the Civil List and Secret Service Money Act 1782 (22 Geo.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Initially mandated by an Order in Council on 5 March 1784, the committee was reconstructed and strengthened by a second order, on 23 August 1786, under which it operated for the rest of its existence.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The committee has been known as the Board of Trade since 1786, but this name was only officially adopted by section 65 of the Harbours and Passing Tolls, &c.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The new board's first functions were consultative like earlier iterations, and its concern with plantations, in matters such as the approval of colonial laws, more successfully accomplished.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] As the Industrial Revolution expanded, the board's work became increasingly executive and domestic.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] From the 1840s, a succession of acts of Parliament gave it regulatory duties, notably concerning railways, merchant shipping and joint-stock companies.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] This department was merged with the Ministry of Technology in 1970, to form the Department of Trade and Industry.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Secretary of State for Trade and Industry (from 2009 Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills) was also President of the Board of Trade.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The full board has met only once since the mid-20th century, during commemorations of the bicentenary of the board in 1986.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In 2016, the role of President of the Board of Trade was transferred to the Secretary of State for International Trade.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board was reconstituted in October 2017.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board's formal title remains "The Lords of the Committee of the Privy Council appointed for the consideration of all matters relating to Trade and Foreign Plantations".
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In 1634, Charles I appointed a new commission for regulating plantations.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] It was headed by the Archbishop of Canterbury with its primary goals to increase royal authority and the influence of the Church of England in the colonies, particularly with the great influx of Puritans to the New World.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Soon after, the English Civil Wars erupted and initiated a long period of political instability in England and the resultant loss of productivity for these committees.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The war spread to varying degrees to the English colonies, depending on the internal demographics and political and religious division of each.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Between 1643 and 1648 the Long Parliament established a parliamentary Commission for Plantations to take the lead in colonial and commercial affairs.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] This period also saw the first regulation of royal tonnage and poundage and begin the modernization of customs and excise as growing sources of government revenue.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] During the Interregnum and Commonwealth three acts of the Rump Parliament in 1650 and 1651 are notable in the historical development of England's commercial and colonial programs.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] These include the first Commission of Trade to be established by an Act of Parliament on 1 August 1650.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The act's statesmanlike and comprehensive instructions, along with an October act prohibiting trade with pro-royalist colonies and the Navigation Act of October 1651, formed the first definitive expression of England's commercial policy.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] They represent the first attempt to establish a legitimate control of commercial and colonial affairs, and the instructions indicate the beginnings of a policy which had the prosperity and wealth of England exclusively at heart.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] It was the Lords of Trade who, in 1675, originated the idea of transforming all of the colonies in America into Royal Colonies for the purpose of securing English trade against the French.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Mercantile losses during the Nine Years' War, and the currency crisis that led to the Great Recoinage of 1696, led to several proposals during the early 1690s for a more effective "council of trade" to advise the government.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Reformers like Charles Davenant pushed for a council in which merchant representatives were seated, with extensive powers to regulate trade.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] These proposals were vigorously debated in the 3rd Parliament of William III, and became the substrate for partisan jousting, with the Court party proposing a scheme of royally-appointed commissioners, while the Country party pressed for a board appointed by Parliament.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The reaction to the 1696 Jacobite assassination plot ensured that the Court plan carried the day, but with only marginally increased powers over the old committee, scrapping more radical reform in deference to politics surrounding the royal prerogative.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In May 1696, the old committee of the Privy Council was dissolved and its powers transferred to the new board of Commissioners for Trade and Plantations.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Eight paid commissioners, over whom the senior, or "First Lord", presided, carried out the regular work of the commission.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Staff appointed to serve the board in 1696 included a secretary, a deputy secretary, some clerks, office keepers, messengers, and a necessary woman; more staff such as a solicitor and a porter were added later.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Bishop of London was added to the *ex officio* commissioners in 1702, and the Surveyor and Auditor-General of the Plantations in 1721.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The commission carried on the work of the former Lords of Trade but also had long periods of inactivity, devolving into chaos after 1761.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Council was dismissed by George III of Great Britain on 2 May 1782 and dissolved on 11 July 1782 by the Civil List and Secret Service Money Act 1782.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] William Pitt the Younger re-established the committee of the Privy Council in 1784, and an Order in Council of 23 August 1786 provided the formal basis that still remains in force.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] A secretariat was established which included the president, vice president and board members.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] By 1793, the board still remained in its old structure, with 20 members including the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] After 1820 the board ceased to meet regularly and the business was carried out entirely by the secretariat.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The short name of "Board of Trade" was formalised in 1861.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In the 19th century the board had an advisory function on economic activity in the UK and its empire.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] During the second half of the 19th century, it also dealt with legislation for patents, designs and trademarks, company regulation, labour and factories, merchant shipping, agriculture, transport, power etc.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Colonial matters passed to the Colonial Office and other functions were devolved to newly created departments, a process that continued for much of the 20th century.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The original commission comprised the seven (later eight) Great Officers of State, who were not required to attend meetings, and the eight paid members, who were required to attend.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board, so constituted, had little real power, and matters related to trade and the colonies were usually within the jurisdiction of the secretaries of state and the Privy Council, with the board confining itself mainly to colonial administration.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In 1905, David Lloyd George entered the new Liberal Cabinet of Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman as President of the Board of Trade.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The first priority on taking office was the repeal of the Education Act 1902.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Lloyd George took the lead along with Augustine Birrell, President of the Board of Education.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Lloyd George was the dominant figure on the committee drawing up the bill in its later stages and insisted that the bill create a separate education committee for Wales.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The bill passed the House of Commons greatly amended but was completely mangled by the House of Lords.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] No compromise was possible and the bill was abandoned, allowing the 1902 act to continue in effect.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Nonconformists were bitterly upset by the failure of the Liberal Party to reform the Education Act 1902, its most important promise to them, and over time their support for the Liberal Party slowly fell away.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] According to Martin Roberts, Lloyd George headed a department of 750 experts that was responsible for supervising British industry, commerce and transportation.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Using their pool of expertise, he initiated a series of reforms that were quickly endorsed by the Liberal Parliament.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] One of the first actions was the Census of Production Act 1906 (6 Edw.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] 49), which generated a Survey of production—an up-to-date compendium of detailed statistics necessary for regulating specific industries.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Merchant Shipping Act 1906 upgraded the minimum working conditions, and the safety protections for both British sailors, and crews of foreign ships that used British ports.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Patents and Design Act 1907 gave financial protection to British designs to stop unfair foreign copies.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In the long term, his most important innovation was the Port of London Act 1908 creating the Port of London Authority.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] It merged numerous inefficient and overlapping private companies and gave unified supervision to Britain's most important port.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] That enabled London to compete more effectively with Hamburg and Rotterdam.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Lloyd George also turned his attention to strikes and industrial disputes in shipyards.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] He was instrumental in settling the serious threat of a national railway strike in 1907.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] While almost all the rail companies refused to recognise the unions, he persuaded them to recognise elected representatives of the workers who sat with the company representatives on conciliation boards—one for each company.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] If those boards failed to agree then an arbitrator would be called upon.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Asquith succeeded the terminally ill prime minister on 8 April 1908 and, four days later, Winston Churchill was appointed President of the Board of Trade, succeeding Lloyd George who became Chancellor of the Exchequer.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] He continued the reform impulse Lloyd George had launched.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] One of Churchill's first tasks was to arbitrate in an industrial dispute among ship-workers and employers on the River Tyne.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] He afterwards established a Standing Court of Arbitration to deal with future industrial disputes, establishing a reputation as a conciliator.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In Cabinet, he worked with Lloyd George to champion social reform.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] He promoted what he called a "network of State intervention and regulation" akin to that in Germany.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Churchill's main achievements came in 1909.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] It set up over 200 labour exchanges with William Beveridge in charge.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The unemployed would come in and be assisted in finding employment.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] He also promoted the idea of an unemployment insurance scheme, which would be part-funded by the state.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Secondly he introduced the Trade Boards Bill, creating trade boards which investigated the sweated trades and enabled the prosecution of exploitative employers.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Passing with a large majority, it established the principle of a minimum wage and the right of workers to have meal breaks.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Churchill introduced the Mines Eight Hours Bill, which legally prohibited miners from working more than an eight-hour day.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] Sydney Buxton served as president between 1910 and 1914.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] His main role was passage of numerous specific trade and commerce laws.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] From 1973, international trade policy of the United Kingdom was a competence of the European Economic Community, and later of the European Union.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The board was reconstituted in October 2017, after the UK had voted to leave the European Union in June 2016.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] In its most recent iteration in 2017, only privy counsellors can be actual members of the board, while others are appointed as advisers.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] There is only one standing member in the Board, who is its President.
[src:alfred-holt/board-of-trade] The Board is held accountable to Parliament through ministers attached to the Board, who are not necessarily members.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The **Cape of Good Hope** (Afrikaans: *Kaap de Goede Hoop* [ˌkaːb də ˌɣudə ˈɦoːp] ⓘ; Portuguese: *Cabo da Boa Esperança* [ˈkaβu ðɐ ˈβoɐ (ɨ)ʃpɨˈɾɐ̃sɐ]) is a rocky headland on the Atlantic coast of the Cape Peninsula in South Africa.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] A common misconception is that the Cape of Good Hope is the southern tip of Africa, based on the misbelief that the Cape was the dividing point between the Atlantic and Indian oceans.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In fact, the southernmost point of Africa is Cape Agulhas about 150 kilometres (90 mi) to the east-southeast.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The currents of the two oceans meet at the point where the warm-water Agulhas current meets the cold-water Benguela current and turns back on itself.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] That oceanic meeting point fluctuates between Cape Agulhas and Cape Point (about 1.2 kilometres (0.75 mi) east of the Cape of Good Hope).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] is the southernmost part of South Africa.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] When following the western side of the African coastline from the equator, however, the Cape of Good Hope marks the point where a ship begins to travel more eastward than southward.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Thus, the first modern rounding of the cape in 1487 by Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias was a milestone in the attempts by the Portuguese to establish direct trade relations with the Far East (although Herodotus mentioned a claim that the Phoenicians had done so far earlier).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Dias called the cape *Cabo das Tormentas* ('Cape of Storms'; Dutch: *Stormkaap*), which was the original name of the cape.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] As one of the great capes of the South Atlantic Ocean, it has long been of special significance to sailors, many of whom refer to it simply as "**the Cape**".
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] It is a waypoint on the Cape Route and the clipper route followed by clipper ships to the Far East and Australia, and still followed by several offshore yacht races.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Around 600 BC, Necho II reputedly commissioned an expedition of Phoenicians, who are said to have sailed for three years from the Red Sea around Africa back to the mouth of the Nile; and this would thereby be the first completion of the Cape Route.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] 130 BC) was a Greek navigator for Ptolemy VIII, king of the Hellenistic Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In or about 116 BCE, while returning from a voyage to India, Eudoxus found the wreck of a ship that appeared to have originated in Gades (later Cádiz), in what was then Roman Hispania Baetica.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] At the time, the only way such a vessel could have reached the Indian Ocean was by rounding the Cape.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] When Eudoxus was returning from his second voyage to India, the wind forced him south of the Gulf of Aden and down the coast of Africa for some distance.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Somewhere along the coast of East Africa, he found the remains of the ship.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Due to its appearance and the story told by the natives, Eudoxus concluded that the ship was from Gades and had sailed anti-clockwise around Africa, passing the Cape and entering the Indian Ocean.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] This inspired him to repeat the voyage and attempt a circumnavigation of the continent.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Organising the expedition on his own account, he set sail from Gades and began to work down the African coast.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The difficulties were too great, however, and he was obliged to return to Europe.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] After this failure, he again set out to circumnavigate Africa.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Although some, such as Pliny, claimed that Eudoxus did achieve his goal, the most probable conclusion is that he died on the journey.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In the 1450 Fra Mauro map, the Indian Ocean is depicted as connected to the Atlantic.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] This knowledge, together with the map depiction of the African continent, probably encouraged the Portuguese to intensify their effort to round the tip of Africa.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In 1511, after Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca, the Portuguese recovered a chart from a Javanese maritime pilot, which, according to Albuquerque, already included the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In the Early Modern Era, the first European to reach the cape was the Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias on 12 March 1488, who named it the "Cape of Storms" (*Cabo das Tormentas*).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] It was later renamed by John II of Portugal as "Cape of Good Hope" (*Cabo da Boa Esperança*) because of the great optimism engendered by the opening of a sea route to India and the East.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Khoikhoi people lived in the cape area when the Dutch first settled there in 1652.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Khoikhoi had arrived in this area about fifteen hundred years before.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch called them *Hottentots*, a term that has now come to be regarded as pejorative.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In 1652, the Dutch East India Company's administrator Jan van Riebeeck established a resupply camp for the Dutch East India Company some 50 km north of the cape in Table Bay on April 6, and this eventually developed into Cape Town.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Supplies of fresh food were vital on the long journey around Africa and Cape Town became known as "The Tavern of the Seas".
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] On 31 December 1687, a community of Huguenots (French Protestants) arrived at the Cape of Good Hope from the Netherlands.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] They had fled from France due to religious persecution and gone to the Netherlands, before making the journey to the Cape Colony.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Members of this group included Pierre Joubert, who came from La Motte-d'Aigues, as well as Jean Roy.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch East India Company needed skilled farmers at the Cape of Good Hope and the Dutch government saw opportunities to settle Huguenots at the Cape.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The colony gradually grew over the 150 years that followed until it extended hundreds of kilometers to the north and the north-east.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] During the French Revolutionary Wars, the Dutch Republic was occupied by the French in 1795.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape Colony then became a French vassal and enemy of the British, who were at war with France.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] British troops invaded and occupied the Cape Colony that same year.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The British relinquished control of the territory in 1803, under the peace of Amiens, but reoccupied the colony on 19 January 1806 following the Battle of Blaauwberg.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch formally ceded the territory to the British in the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1814.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] It would remain a separate British colony until its incorporation into the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Portuguese government erected two navigational beacons, **Dias Cross** and **da Gama Cross**, to commemorate Bartolomeu Dias and Vasco da Gama, who were the first modern European explorers to reach the cape.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] When lined up, these crosses point to Whittle Rock, a large, permanently submerged shipping hazard in False Bay.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Two other beacons in Simon's Town provide the intersection.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope saw an increase of ship activity after the 2021 Suez canal obstruction, and the Red Sea Crisis with ships needing a different route from the Indian Ocean.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope route took a toll on the sea freight industry—stretching the transit time, reducing carriers availability, and skyrocketing shipment cost and container hire.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Carriers' attempts to resort to the Red Sea route came at the expense of vessels and seafarers' safety as the Red Sea witnessed multiple sunken carriers struck by Houthi rebels.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Many large shipping companies and industries were afflicted by the situation such as IKEA, Amazon, Automotive companies, and Maersk.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope is at the southern tip of the Cape Peninsula, about 2.3 kilometers (1.4 mi) west and a little north of Cape Point on the south-east corner.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Cape Town is about 50 kilometers to the north of the Cape, in Table Bay at the north end of the peninsula.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The peninsula forms the western boundary of False Bay.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Geologically, the rocks found at the two capes, and indeed over much of the peninsula, are part of the Cape Supergroup, and are formed of the same type of sandstones as Table Mountain itself.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Both the Cape of Good Hope and Cape Point offer spectacular scenery; the whole of the southernmost portion of the Cape Peninsula is a wild, rugged, scenic and generally unspoiled national park.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The term "the Cape" has also been used in a wider sense, to indicate the area of the European colony centered on Cape Town, and the later South African province.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Since 1994, it has been broken up into three smaller provinces: the Western Cape, Eastern Cape, and Northern Cape; parts of the province were also absorbed into the North West.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] With its diverse habitat, ranging from rocky mountain tops to beaches and open sea, the Cape of Good Hope is home to at least 250 species of birds including one of the two mainland colonies of African penguins.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] "Bush birds" tend to be rather scarce because of the coarse, scrubby nature of fynbos vegetation.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] When flowering, however, proteas and ericas attract sunbirds, sugarbirds, and other species in search of nectar.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] For most of the year, there are more small birds in coastal thicket than in fynbos.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope section of Table Mountain National Park is home to several species of antelope.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Bontebok and eland are easily seen, and red hartebeest can be seen in the grazing lawns in Smitswinkel Flats.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Grey rhebok are less commonly seen and are scarce, but may be observed along the beach hills at Olifantsbos.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Most visitors are unlikely to ever see either Cape grysbok or klipspringer.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope section is home to four Cape mountain zebra.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] They might be seen by the attentive or lucky visitor, usually in Smitswinkel Flats.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] There are a wealth of small animals such as lizards, snakes, tortoises and insects.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Small mammals include rock hyrax, four-striped grass mouse, water mongoose, Cape clawless otter and fallow deer.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The area offers excellent vantage points for whale watching.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The southern right whale is the species most likely to be seen in False Bay between June and November.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Other species are the humpback whale and Bryde's whale.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Seals, dusky dolphins and orcas have also been seen.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The strategic position of the Cape of Good Hope between two major ocean currents, ensures a rich diversity of marine life.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] There is a difference between the sea life west of Cape Point and that to the east due to the markedly differing sea temperatures.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The South African Marine Living Resources Act is strictly enforced throughout the Table Mountain National Park, and especially in marine protected areas.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Disturbance or removal of any marine organisms is strictly prohibited between Schusters Bay and Hoek van Bobbejaan, but is allowed in other areas during season and with relevant permits.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Chacma baboons (*Papio ursinus*) are the mammals most intimately associated with the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Baboons inside the Cape of Good Hope section of the park are a major tourist attraction.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] There are 11 troops consisting of about 375 individuals throughout the entire Cape Peninsula.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Six of these 11 troops either live entirely within the Cape of Good Hope section of the park, or use the section as part of their range.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape Point, Kanonkop, Klein Olifantsbos, and Buffels Bay troops live entirely inside the Cape of Good Hope section of the Park.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Groot Olifantsbos and Plateau Road troops range into the park.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Chacma baboons are widely distributed across southern Africa and are classified as "least concern" in the *IUCN Red List of Threatened Species*.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] However, the South African Parks Department states in its publication *Mountains in the Sea* that the baboon population on the Cape is "critically endangered." This is due to habitat loss, genetic isolation, and conflicts with humans.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Cape baboons have been eliminated from the majority of their range across the Cape Peninsula, and the Cape of Good Hope section of Table Mountain National Park provides a sanctuary for the troops that live within its boundaries.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] It provides relative safety from nearby towns, where people have killed many baboons after the baboons raid their houses looking for food.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Baboons are also frequently injured or killed outside of the park by cars and by electrocution on power lines.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Inside the park, some management policies such as allowing barbecues and picnics in the baboon home ranges cause detriment to the troops, as they become embroiled in conflicts with guests to the park.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] At the Cape in particular, the baboon is known for eating shellfish and other marine invertebrates.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] In 1842, Charles Hamilton Smith had described a black-maned lion from the Cape under the scientific name *Felis (Leo) melanochaita*.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] No longer seen as a subspecies of its own, the Cape lion as a population is now extinct in the wilderness, though descendants could exist in captivity.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope is an integral part of the Cape Floristic Kingdom, the smallest but richest of the world's six floral kingdoms.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] This comprises a treasure trove of 1100 species of indigenous plants, of which a number are endemic (occur naturally nowhere else on earth).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] The main type of fynbos ("fine bush") vegetation at the Cape of Good Hope is Peninsula Sandstone Fynbos, an endangered vegetation type that is endemic to the Cape Peninsula.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Coastal Hangklip Sand Fynbos grows on low-lying alkaline sands and, right by the sea, small patches of Cape Flats Dune Strandveld can be found.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Characteristic fynbos plants include proteas, ericas (heath), and restios (reeds).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Some of the most striking and well-known members belong to the Proteaceae family, of which up to 24 species occur.
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] These include king protea, sugarbush, tree pincushion and golden cone bush (*Leucadendron laureolum*).
[src:alfred-holt/cape-of-good-hope] Many popular horticultural plants like pelargoniums, freesias, daisies, lilies and irises also have their origins in fynbos.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A **clipper** was a type of mid-19th-century merchant sailing vessel, designed for speed.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The term was also retrospectively applied to the Baltimore clipper, which originated in the late 18th century.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clippers were generally narrow for their length, small by later 19th-century standards, could carry limited bulk freight, and had a large total sail area.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] "Clipper" does not refer to a specific sailplan; clippers may be schooners, brigs, brigantines, etc., as well as full-rigged ships.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clippers were mostly constructed in British and American shipyards, although France, Brazil, the Netherlands, and other nations also produced some.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clippers sailed all over the world, primarily on the trade routes between the United Kingdom and China, in transatlantic trade, and on the New York-to-San Francisco route around Cape Horn during the California gold rush.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Dutch clippers were built beginning in the 1850s for the tea trade and passenger service to Java.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The boom years of the clipper era began in 1843 in response to a growing demand for faster delivery of tea from China and continued with the demand for swift passage to gold fields in California and Australia beginning in 1848 and 1851, respectively.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The era ended with the opening of the Panama Railroad in 1855 and the Suez Canal in 1869.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The etymological origin of the word clipper is uncertain, but is believed to be derived from the English language verb "to clip", which at the time meant "to run or fly swiftly".
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The first application of the term "clipper", in a nautical sense, is likewise uncertain.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The type known as the Baltimore clipper originated at the end of the 18th century on the eastern seaboard of the United States.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] At first, these fast sailing vessels were referred to as "Virginia-built" or "pilot-boat model", with the name "Baltimore-built" appearing during the War of 1812.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In the final days of the slave trade (*circa* 1835–1850) – just as the type was dying out – the term, Baltimore clipper, came into frequent use.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The common retrospective application of the word "clipper" to this type of vessel has caused confusion.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The Oxford English Dictionary's earliest quote (referring to the Baltimore clipper) is from 1824.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The dictionary cites Royal Navy officer and novelist Frederick Marryat as using the term in 1830.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] British newspaper usage of the term can be found as early as 1832 and in shipping advertisements from 1835.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A US court case of 1834 has evidence that discusses a clipper being faster than a brig.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A clipper is a sailing vessel designed for speed, a priority that takes precedence over cargo-carrying capacity or building or operating costs.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] It is not restricted to any one rig (while many were fully rigged ships, others were barques, brigs, or schooners), nor was the term restricted to any one hull type.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Howard Chapelle lists three basic hull types for clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The first was characterised by the sharp deadrise and ends found in the Baltimore clipper.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The second was a hull with a full midsection and modest deadrise, but sharp ends – this was a development of the hull form of transatlantic packets.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The third was more experimental, with deadrise and sharpness being balanced against the need to carry a profitable quantity of cargo.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A clipper carried a large sail area and a fast hull; by the standards of any other type of sailing ship, a clipper was greatly over-canvassed.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The last defining feature of a clipper, in the view of maritime historian David MacGregor, was a captain who had the courage, skill, and determination to get the fastest speed possible out of her.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In assessing the hull of a clipper, different maritime historians use different criteria to measure "sharpness", "fine lines" or "fineness", a concept which is explained by comparing a rectangular cuboid with the underwater shape of a vessel's hull.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The more material one has to carve off the cuboid to achieve the hull shape, the sharper the hull.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Ideally, a maritime historian would be able to look at either the block coefficient of fineness or the prismatic coefficient of various clippers, but measured drawings or accurate half models may not exist to calculate either of these figures.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] An alternative measure of sharpness for hulls of a broadly similar shape is the coefficient of underdeck tonnage, as used by David MacGregor in comparing tea clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This could be calculated from the measurements taken to determine the registered tonnage, so can be applied to more vessels.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] An extreme clipper has a hull of great fineness, as judged either by the prismatic coefficient, the coefficient of underdeck tonnage, or some other technical assessment of hull shape.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This term has been misapplied in the past, without reference to hull shape.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] As commercial vessels, these are totally reliant on speed to generate a profit for their owners, as their sharpness limits their cargo-carrying capacity.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A medium clipper has a cargo-carrying hull that has some sharpness.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In the right conditions and with a capable captain, some of these achieved notable quick passages.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They were also able to pay their way when the high freight rates often paid to a fast sailing ship were not available (in a fluctuating market).
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The term "clipper" applied to vessels between these two categories.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They often made passages as fast as extreme clippers, but had less difficulty in making a living when freight rates were lower.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The first ships to which the term "clipper" seems to have been applied were the Baltimore clippers, developed in the Chesapeake Bay before the American Revolution, and reached their zenith between 1795 and 1815.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They were small, rarely exceeding 200 tons OM.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Their hulls were sharp ended and displayed much deadrise.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They were rigged as schooners, brigs, or brigantines.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In the War of 1812, some were lightly armed, sailing under letters of marque and reprisal, when the type – exemplified by *Chasseur*, launched at Fells Point, Baltimore in 1814 – became known for her incredible speed; the deep draft enabled the Baltimore clipper to sail close to the wind.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clippers, running the British blockade of Baltimore, came to be recognized for speed rather than cargo space.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A 1789 drawing of HMS *Berbice* (1780) – purchased by the Royal Navy in 1780 in the West Indies – represents the earliest draught of what became known as the Baltimore clipper.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Vessels of the Baltimore clipper type continued to be built for the slave trade, being useful for escaping enforcement of the British and American legislation prohibiting the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Some of these Baltimore clippers were captured when working as slavers, condemned by the appropriate court, and sold to owners who then used them as opium clippers – moving from one illegal international trade to another.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In Aberdeen, Scotland, shipbuilders Alexander Hall and Sons developed the "Aberdeen" clipper bow in the late 1830s; the first was *Scottish Maid* launched in 1839.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] *Scottish Maid*, 150 tons OM, was the first British clipper ship.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] "*Scottish Maid* was intended for the Aberdeen-London trade, where speed was crucial to compete with steamships.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The Hall brothers tested various hulls in a water tank and found the clipper design most effective.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The design was influenced by tonnage regulations.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Tonnage measured a ship's cargo capacity and was used to calculate tax and harbour dues.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The new 1836 regulations measured depth and breadth with length measured at half midship depth.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Extra length above this level was tax-free and became a feature of clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] *Scottish Maid* proved swift and reliable and the design was widely copied." The earliest British clipper ships were built for trade within the British Isles (*Scottish Maid* was built for the Aberdeen to London trade).
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Then followed the vast clipper trade of tea, opium, spices, and other goods from the Far East to Europe, and the ships became known as "tea clippers".
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] From 1839, larger American clipper ships started to be built beginning with *Akbar*, 650 tons OM, in 1839, and including the 1844-built *Houqua*, 581 tons OM.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] These larger vessels were built predominantly for use in the China tea trade and known as "tea clippers".
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Then in 1845 *Rainbow*, 757 tons OM, the first extreme clipper, was launched in New York.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] These American clippers were larger vessels designed to sacrifice cargo capacity for speed.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They had a bow lengthened above the water, a drawing out and sharpening of the forward body, and the greatest breadth further aft.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Extreme clippers were built in the period 1845 to 1855.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In 1851, shipbuilders in Medford, Massachusetts, built what is sometimes called one of the first medium clippers, the *Antelope*, often called the *Antelope of Boston* to distinguish her from other ships of the same name.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A contemporary ship-design journalist noted that "the design of her model was to combine large stowage capacity with good sailing qualities." *Antelope* was relatively flat-floored and had only an 8-inch deadrise at half-floor.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The medium clipper, though still very fast, could carry more cargo.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] After 1854, extreme clippers were replaced in American shipbuilding yards by medium clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The *Flying Cloud* was a clipper ship built in 1851 that established the fastest passage between New York and San Francisco within weeks of her launching, then broke her own records three years later, which stood at 89 days 8 hours until 1989.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] (The other contender for this "blue ribbon" title was the medium clipper *Andrew Jackson* – an unresolvable argument exists over timing these voyages "from pilot to pilot").
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] *Flying Cloud* was the most famous of the clippers built by Donald McKay.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] She was known for her extremely close race with the *Hornet* in 1853; for having a woman navigator, Eleanor Creesy, wife of Josiah Perkins Creesy, who skippered the *Flying Cloud* on two record-setting voyages from New York to San Francisco; and for sailing in the Australia and timber trades.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clipper ships largely ceased being built in American shipyards in 1859 when, unlike the earlier boom years, only four clipper ships were built; a few were built in the 1860s.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] British clipper ships continued to be built after 1859.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] From 1859, a new design was developed for British clipper ships that was nothing like the American clippers; these ships continued to be called extreme clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The new design had a sleek, graceful appearance, less sheer, less freeboard, lower bulwarks, and smaller breadth.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] They were built for the China tea trade, starting with *Falcon* in 1859, and continuing until 1870.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The earlier ships were made from wood, though some were made from iron, just as some British clippers had been made from iron prior to 1859.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In 1863, the first tea clippers of composite construction were brought out, combining the best of both worlds.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Composite clippers had the strength of an iron hull framework but with wooden planking that, with properly insulated fastenings, could use copper sheathing without the problem of galvanic corrosion.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Copper sheathing prevented fouling and teredo worm, but could not be used on iron hulls.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The iron framework of composite clippers was less bulky and lighter, so allowing more cargo in a hull of the same external shape.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] After 1869, with the opening of the Suez Canal that greatly advantaged steam vessels (see Decline below), the tea trade collapsed for clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] From the late 1860s until the early 1870s, the clipper trade increasingly focused on the Britain to Australia and New Zealand route, carrying goods and immigrants, services that had begun earlier with the Australian Gold Rush of the 1850s.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] British-built clipper ships and many American-built, British-owned ships were used.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Even in the 1880s, sailing ships were still the main carriers of cargo between Britain, and Australia and New Zealand.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This trade eventually became unprofitable, and the ageing clipper fleet became unseaworthy.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Before the early 18th century, the East India Company paid for its tea mainly in silver.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] When the Chinese emperor chose to embargo European-manufactured commodities and demand payment for all Chinese goods in silver, the price rose, restricting trade.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The East India Company began to produce opium in India, something desired by the Chinese as much as tea was by the British.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This had to be smuggled into China on smaller, fast-sailing ships, called "opium clippers".
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Some of these were built specifically for the purpose – mostly in India and Britain, such as the 1842-built *Ariel*, 100 tons OM.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Some fruit schooners were bought for this trade, as were some Baltimore clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Among the most notable clippers were the China clippers, also called tea clippers, designed to ply the trade routes between Europe and the East Indies.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The last example of these still in reasonable condition is *Cutty Sark*, preserved in dry dock at Greenwich, United Kingdom.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Damaged by fire on 21 May 2007 while undergoing conservation, the ship was permanently elevated 3.0 m above the dry dock floor in 2010 as part of a plan for long-term preservation.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Clippers were built for seasonal trades such as tea, where an early cargo was more valuable, or for passenger routes.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] One passenger ship survives, the *City of Adelaide* designed by William Pile of Sunderland.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The fast ships were ideally suited to low-volume, high-profit goods, such as tea, opium, spices, people, and mail.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The *Challenger* returned from Shanghai with "the most valuable cargo of tea and silk ever to be laden in one bottom".
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Competition among the clippers was public and fierce, with their times recorded in the newspapers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The last China clippers had peak speeds over 16 knots (30 km/h), but their average speeds over a whole voyage were substantially less.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The joint winner of the Great Tea Race of 1866 logged about 15,800 nautical miles on a 99-day trip.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This gives an average speed slightly over 6.6 knots (12.2 km/h).
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The key to a fast passage for a tea clipper was getting across the China Sea against the monsoon winds that prevailed when the first tea crop of the season was ready.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] These difficult sailing conditions (light and/or contrary winds) dictated the design of tea clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The US clippers were designed for the strong winds encountered on their route around Cape Horn.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Donald McKay's *Sovereign of the Seas* reported the highest speed ever achieved by a sailing ship of the era, 22 knots (41 km/h), made while running her easting down to Australia in 1854.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] (John Griffiths' first clipper, the *Rainbow*, had a top speed of 14 knots.) Eleven other instances are reported of a ship's logging 18 knots (33 km/h) or over.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Ten of these were recorded by American clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Besides the breath-taking 465-nautical-mile (861 km) day's run of the *Champion of the Seas*, 13 other cases are known of a ship's sailing over 400 nautical miles (740 km) in 24 hours.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] With few exceptions, though, all the port-to-port sailing records are held by the American clippers.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The 24-hour record of the *Champion of the Seas*, set in 1854, was not broken until 1984 (by a multihull), or 2001 (by another monohull).
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The American clippers sailing from the East Coast to the California goldfields were working in a booming market.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Freight rates were high everywhere in the first years of the 1850s.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The ports of California and Australia reported that they were overstocked with goods that had been shipped earlier in the year.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This gave an accelerating fall in freight rates that was halted, however, by the start of the Crimean War in March 1854, as many ships were now being chartered by the French and British governments.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The end of the Crimean War in April 1856 released all this capacity back on the world shipping markets – the result being a severe slump.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The next year had the Panic of 1857, with effects on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The United States was just starting to recover from this in 1861 when the American Civil War started, causing significant disruption to trade in both Union and Confederate states.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] As the economic situation deteriorated in 1853, American shipowners either did not order new vessels, or specified an ordinary clipper or a medium clipper instead of an extreme clipper.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] No extreme clipper was launched in an American shipyard after the end of 1854 and only a few medium clippers after 1860.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] By contrast, British trade recovered well at the end of the 1850s.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Tea clippers had continued to be launched during the depressed years, apparently little affected by the economic downturn.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The long-distance route to China was not realistically challenged by steamships in the early part of the 1860s.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] No true steamer (as opposed to an auxiliary steamship) had the fuel efficiency to carry sufficient cargo to make a profitable voyage.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The auxiliary steamships struggled to make any profit.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The situation changed in 1866 when the Alfred Holt-designed and owned SS *Agamemnon* made her first voyage to China.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Holt had persuaded the Board of Trade to allow higher steam pressures in British merchant vessels.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Running at 60 psi instead of the previously permitted 25 psi, and using an efficient compound engine, *Agamemnon* had the fuel efficiency to steam at 10 knots to China and back, with coaling stops at Mauritius on the outward and return legs – crucially carrying sufficient cargo to make a profit.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] In 1869, the Suez Canal opened, giving steamships a route about 3,000 nautical miles (5,600 km; 3,500 mi) shorter than that taken by sailing ships round the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Despite initial conservatism by tea merchants, by 1871, tea clippers found strong competition from steamers in the tea ports of China.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] A typical passage time back to London for a steamer was 58 days, while the fastest clippers could occasionally make the trip in less than 100 days; the average was 123 days in the 1867–68 tea season.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The freight rate for a steamer in 1871 was roughly double that paid to a sailing vessel.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Some clipper owners were severely caught out by this; several extreme clippers had been launched in 1869, including *Cutty Sark*, *Norman Court* and *Caliph*.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Of the many clipper ships built during the mid-19th century, only two are known to survive.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The only intact survivor is *Cutty Sark*, which was preserved as a museum ship in 1954 at Greenwich for public display.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The other known survivor is *City of Adelaide*; unlike *Cutty Sark*, she was reduced to a hulk over the years.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] She eventually sank at her moorings in 1991, but was raised the following year, and remained on dry land for years.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] *Carrick*) is the older of the two survivors, and was transported to Australia for conservation.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Departures of clipper ships, mostly from New York and Boston to San Francisco, were advertised by clipper-ship sailing cards.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] These cards, slightly larger than today's postcards, were produced by letterpress and wood engraving on coated card stock.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] Most clipper cards were printed in the 1850s and 1860s, and represented the first pronounced use of color in American advertising art.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] With their rarity and importance as artifacts of nautical, Western, and printing history, clipper cards are valued by both private collectors and institutions.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The Los Angeles Clippers of the National Basketball Association take their name from the type of ship.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] After the Buffalo Braves moved to San Diego, California in 1978, a contest was held to choose a new name.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The winning name highlighted the city's connection with the clippers that frequented San Diego Bay.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The team retained the name in its 1984 move to Los Angeles.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The airline Pan Am named its aircraft beginning with the word 'Clipper' and used Clipper as its callsign.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] This was intended to evoke an image of speed and glamour.
[src:alfred-holt/clipper] The Europa Clipper is a NASA probe that is currently on a mission to explore Jupiter and its moons; it was launched in 2024 and is expected to reach Jupiter in 2030.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club's biggest accomplishments are winning the Scottish Cup on three occasions: 1939, 1955 and 1958; they reached the final a further three times, all during a long period based at Shawfield, in Rutherglen.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They have not played in the top division of Scottish football since 1975.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club have been managed by Darren Young since October 2024.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde Football Club was founded and played on the banks of the River Clyde at Barrowfield.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Documentary evidence from the SFA and indeed match reports in the Glasgow press clearly show it all began in 1877, and the thread continues unbroken to this day.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Sitting on the edge of Bridgeton, Barrowfield Park lay in a triangle of land enclosed by Carstairs Street, Colvend Street and the river Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The area was an intense mix of chemical, engineering and textile work with a high population density to provide the labour.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Although no stadium photographs have emerged, it appears the ground consisted of a grandstand running north–south, a pavilion and tennis courts at the southern end and a bicycle track surrounding the pitch.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Today this area is dotted with industrial units, but also contains a large grassed area, so it may be possible to stand upon a corner of the original Barrowfield pitch.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Barrowfield got initially shared with a short-lived team called Albatross.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club founded then has no resemblance to a modern professional football club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde F.C. was a private members club more akin to a present-day golf or bowling club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde's Secretary, John Graham, was also a noted rower and it seems the club had other sporting and cultural activities besides football.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Although most fixtures were informal, the Scottish Cup had existed since 1873.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Soon there would also be the Glasgow Merchants Charity Cup and the Glasgow Cup which in their time were hotly contested major competitions.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde entered the 1st round of the Scottish Cup on 29 September 1877 along with one hundred and one other teams.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Third Lanark were the visitors once again, and triumphed 1–0.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 6 March 1883, the Glasgow Football Association was established (formed to compete with the older - 1877 - rival Edinburgh Association), with Clyde one of the six clubs represented at that first meeting.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club are one of only three founding members clubs still in existence today (with Queen's Park and Rangers).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde joined the Scottish Football League in 1891, its second edition.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Following acceptance, Vale of Leven provided the opposition for Clyde's first League fixture on Saturday, 15 August 1891.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In a dream introduction to the format Clyde triumphed 10–3, and a mid-table finish saw the club complete a confident season in League football.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] While it was an undoubted success, Barrowfield revealed its limitations and could not cope with the crowds as many gained illegal entry.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Opposition teams complained about the facilities, and it was clear that Clyde would have to do something to appease the League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club had the pitch dug up in the off season in 1893 to have the clayey surface replaced by ashes to lend additional facilities to the draining powers of the field.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club enjoyed cup success in local competitions as the 19th century drew to a close.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The team won the North Eastern Cup and Graham Cup four times apiece.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Both tournaments featured teams from the East End of Glasgow.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, Clyde endured a terrible final season at Barrowfield, finishing bottom of Division 1 with only 5 points, but remained in the top division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The last action at Barrowfield was a friendly against crack opposition in the form of Sunderland on 30 April 1898, ending in a 3–3 draw.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club left Barrowfield in 1898 and purchased some open ground (Shawfield) directly across the river between the Glasgow neighbourhood of Oatlands and the Lanarkshire town of Rutherglen.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The move was largely financed by the club becoming incorporated and issuing shares in "The Clyde Football Club Limited".
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Ltd had an enclosed area of about 9 acres (3.6 ha).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A grandstand seating of 1500 was nearing completion and embankment works around the pitch were well underway.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Local rivals Celtic provided the first opposition at Shawfield Stadium on 27 August 1898.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] An attendance of 10,000 witnessed a goalless draw and return gate receipts of £203.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 1899–1900 season saw the team relegated by finishing bottom of top division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They were Division Two champions in 1904–05 (and runners up in 1903–04 and 1905–06), but there was no promotion until the latter second-place finish.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Automatic promotion and relegation was not established until 1921.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The following seasons up to World War I would be far more successful and represented the most consistent period of success for the club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] From 1908 to 1913, Clyde were at the top end of Division One and reached the Scottish Cup final in 1910 and 1912.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The team placed third in 1908–09 (three points behind champions Celtic) and in 1911–12 and reached further semi finals (in 1908–09 and 1912–13).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 1910 final was a bitter disappointment.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] For 83 minutes Clyde (McTurk; Watson & Blair; Walker, McAteer & Robertson; Stirling & McCartney; Chalmers; Jackson & Booth) held a 2–0 lead (Chalmers and Booth both scored).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, Robertson fluffed a clearance off Blair and into his own net.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Dundee then netted a last minute equalizer from Langlands.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The replay was far more cagey and ended goalless after extra time, but with Dundee looking physically stronger.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Chalmers struck after three minutes to give Clyde a 1–0 lead in the third match.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Dundee equalized before half time, and as Clyde looked jaded, John Hunter won the cup for Dundee.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 1912 final was a 2–0 defeat to Celtic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] International honours were awarded to Clyde for the first time in March 1909, as William Walker represented Scotland against club mate Jack Kirwan of Ireland at Ibrox (5–0 to Scotland).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Glasgow Charity Cup (in 1910) and Glasgow Cup (in 1914) were won for the first time.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Both were highly prestigious competitions before European football was introduced.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] All six clubs (Celtic, Clyde, Partick Thistle, Queen's Park, Rangers and Third Lanark) were more often than not resident in Division One.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In September 1914, a fire destroyed the grandstand, and with it much of the club's early history.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After the war broke out in November 1914, the Scottish League would continue playing.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Many players signed up for 'King & Country' – some never returned, such as C.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Sharp (1st Battalion Royal Scots) – and teams like Clyde found it increasingly difficult to field competitive sides and the League eventually reduced back to a single division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club had managed to sustain football through the war years, but the Scottish League continued through 1919–21 with only one division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Division Two restarted in 1921–22, with automatic promotion and relegation adopted.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Benefits were evident for ambitious teams, but the financial penalties for falling out of the top tier were extremely severe.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Relegated in 1923–24, Clyde spent two seasons playing teams like Armadale, Arthurlie, Bathgate, Bo'ness, Broxburn, and King's Park until promotion (and another Glasgow Cup) in 1925–26.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] From 1926 to 1939, Clyde remained a Division One club, as the team maintained a respectable mid-table status.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] International honours returned to Shawfield, as Danny Blair was a prominent Scotland full back of this era and leading goalscorer Billy Boyd (with 32 goals in 1932–33) earned two international caps.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Liquidation was narrowly averted in 1930.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Greyhound racing was booming in the 1920s and many clubs used this a way to supplement their income.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A company offered to lease Shawfield in 1926 and also give a percentage of the gate money to Clyde, but animal racing was forbidden in the deeds of Shawfield and the League was dead set against the sport in general.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Chairman John McMahon would not let go of the idea.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After years of wrangling, the Shawfield Greyhound Racing Company Ltd started racing in 1932 and a few years later purchased the stadium from Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The team conceded a solitary goal on the run to the 1939 Scottish Cup final.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clean sheets were kept against St Johnstone (2–0), Dundee (0–0 at Dens Park, followed by 1–0 in a replay), city rivals Third Lanark (1–0), and the Hibernian semi final match (1–0 at Tynecastle).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The single goal against came at Rangers in the 3rd round, where prolific centre forward Willie Martin set a record for an opposition at Ibrox by scoring all four goals in a 4–1 win.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde (Brown; Kirk and Hickie; Beaton, Falloon and Weir; Robertson and Gillies; Martin; Noble and Wallace) faced Motherwell, who had scored the most goals on route to the final, in front of 94,000 at Hampden on 22 April 1939.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After losing the coin toss, Clyde goalkeeper Brown was under the most pressure early on.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Assisted by a Robertson delivery, Wallace fired the opener in the roof of the net.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Despite further opposition pressure before the interval, Martin doubled the lead with an opportunistic strike after the break.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Late goals from Noble (netting from a rebound) and Martin (assisted by Noble for his second) sealed an emphatic 4–0 win and a maiden Scottish Cup triumph.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] War with Nazi Germany caused the suspension of the Scottish League in 1939–40, and all players' contracts declared void.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Unofficial competitions soon restarted with an East/West regional split.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The geographical separation meant Clyde were placed in the Southern League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Runners up behind champions Rangers in 1940–41 (by three points), the team would continue to perform relatively well in wartime competitions.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A second major cup competition, the Scottish League Cup would be inaugurated in 1946.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It was the then Clyde and SFL chairman John McMahon who donated the trophy that is still awarded to the winners of the competition to this day.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club ventured on a 20-match tour of South Africa in 1947 and recorded 16 wins, 2 draws and 2 defeats.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Also in 1953, future Ballon d'Or winner Stanley Matthews (and Blackpool teammate Ernie Taylor) turned out for Clyde against Everton in a benefit match at Celtic Park in Belfast.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Leslie Johnston, a then Scotland internationalist, twice broke the Scottish transfer record as a Clyde player in the 1940s.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The team showed steady league form just after the war and reached a fourth Scottish Cup final in 1948–49.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In only the fourth edition of the competition since Clyde won it in 1938–39, their opponents Rangers ran out comfortable 4–1 winners in front of a crowd of 108,000 at Hampden, with Peter Galletly scoring Clyde's consolation goal.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It was claimed that both Rangers penalties were of a dubious nature.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 1950s began with relegation from Division A in 1950–51, but returned as Division B champions in 1951–52.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Each occasion saw the team bounce back to solid finishes in Division A.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Floodlighting was introduced at Shawfield in March 1954.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The first opposition was Huddersfield Town in a friendly match.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Domestic cup success came readily in the 1950s.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They also reached Scottish League Cup semi-finals in 1956–57 and 1957–58, but lost on both occasions to Celtic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The route to the 1954–55 Final began with three straight home victories in the competition against Albion Rovers (3–0), Raith Rovers (3–1) and Falkirk (5–0).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Aberdeen provided Clyde's semi-final opponents.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After a 2–2 draw at Easter Road, a solitary goal in the replay sent Clyde into the final.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 23 April 1955 at Hampden in front of over 96,000, Celtic, installed as firm favourites, provided the opposition in the final, in a match that was also the first to be televised live.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Without forward McPhail and goalkeeper Wilson, Clyde lined up:- Hewkins, Murphy & Haddock; Granville, Anderson & Laing; Divers & Robertson; Hill; Brown & Ring.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Celtic held a 1–0 lead with three minutes left until Robertson scored direct from a corner kick to earn a replay.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A crowd of over 68,000 gathered for the replay, with the same Clyde line up, a Tommy Ring goal was enough to win a more open affair.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The first half of the League Cup tie with Aberdeen at Shawfield on 3 September 1955 was also televised live (a competition first) by the BBC as an experiment.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Back at Hampden on 26 April 1958 in front of a crowd of 94,000 to face a strong Hibernian team, Clyde lined up:- McCulloch, Murphy & Haddock; Walters, Finlay & Clinton; Herd & Currie; Coyle; Robertson & Ring.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A deflected strike from Coyle in poor conditions gave Clyde a 1–0 win and a second Scottish Cup in four seasons and third overall.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Fourth place in the final league table and another League Cup semi-final spot completed an impressive season in 1957–58.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Haddock, Robertson and Coyle were confirmed in the final Scotland squad for the 1958 FIFA World Cup.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Dan Currie was selected in the provisional squad, but did not make the final cut.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde gained entry into the Friendship Cup in 1960.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It was an inter-League competition between four clubs each from England, France and Scotland, with results aggregated to provide the 'best' League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It proved to be an unpopular format and ended in 1962.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] For the record, Clyde was drawn against RC Lens of Ligue 1 and beat them 4–0 away and 2–1 at Shawfield.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club began the 1960s as a yo-yo club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Relegations in 1960–61 and 1962–63 were followed by immediate promotions in 1961–62 and 1963–64, the former as Division Two champions.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] At home to Celtic on 10 September 1966, the Clyde team unusually started the match with squad numbers instead of the traditional (1–11) positional numbers on their shirts.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The team actually returned from the interval with the routine numbering of 1–11.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 1966–67 season led Clyde to their highest league finish in forty-five years and another Scottish Cup semi-final appearance.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Competing largely as a part-time team, Clyde finished third behind the Old Firm clubs.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After producing a wonderful season of football that has marked the high tide in the club's fortunes to date, European football will forever love denying itself.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Inter-Cities Fairs Cup had a rule that stipulated only one team per city could enter.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde argued that they were not from Glasgow; they were from Rutherglen.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However UEFA denied this argument citing Clyde's non-membership of the Lanarkshire FA and their participation in the Glasgow Cup.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Another League Cup semi-final was reached in 1968–69.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club journeyed on a 10-match tour of Rhodesia in 1969 and remained unbeaten (9 wins and 1 draw).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] As the 1960s came to a close, Clyde was competing rather comfortably in the top division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It was a different story on the terraces with Glasgow's slum clearance programme hitting attendances hard.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Large swathes of housing in Bridgeton, Dalmarnock, Gorbals, Oatlands and Rutherglen were being demolished with the inhabitants decanted away to other parts of the city and beyond.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde's core support was drawn from these areas, and many of them have never returned to follow the team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club began the 1970s as in previous decades, with the threat of relegation of hanging around.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In an attempt to quit the city, there was an attempted merger with Hamilton Academical, who were in dire financial trouble and had resigned from the Scottish League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After the move floundered as quickly as it arose, Hamilton quickly rejoined the League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Less than a year later, Dumbarton of Division Two made an audacious bid to merge with Clyde in Division One at the time in return for a cash settlement.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Scottish League quickly quashed the move, after viewing it as Dumbarton trying to gain back-door entry into the top division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After relegation in 1971–72, many club legends such as Harry Glasgow, Sam Hastings, Tommy McCulloch, Graham McFarlane and Eddie Mulheron moved on.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde did recover and won promotion as Division Two champions in 1972–73.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Two years in the top division until another relegation in 1974–75 would be their last in the top division to date.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Premier Division was introduced ahead of the season 1975–76 as the new top division, with inclusion based upon league position.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A poor 16th-place finish in Division One in season 1974–75 meant Clyde was never in contention.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club now found themselves back in the second tier, now known as the First Division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club found a new role, discovering and developing talent before selling it on.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Shawfield was the starting point for future Scotland internationalists like Steve Archibald, Ian Ferguson and Pat Nevin.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Problems on and off the pitch saw Clyde move into freefall.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After finishing bottom of the First Division in 1975–76, they found themselves in the Second Division, the third tier, for the season 1976–77.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They only could muster a seventh-place finish.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In a decade Clyde had gone from the third best team in Scotland to a single spot above the finishing last in the Scottish football league system.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Towards the end of the season, Celtic legend Billy McNeill took charge but left for Aberdeen after only a few months at the helm.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club then turned to the relatively unknown Craig Brown, and he had immediate success as the team won the Second Division in 1977–78.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The stadium was falling into a state of disrepair, and the grounds were not well maintained.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] By the late 1970s, Shawfield came into the hands of the Greyhound Racing Association (GRA).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Greyhound racing had been in decline since 1963 when off-course betting was allowed.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] To compensate for this, the GRA had transformed itself into a property company and had a policy of acquiring and redeveloping dog tracks for commercial and residential uses.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They became the first Scottish club to adopt a shirt sponsor in 1979–80.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club secured a deal with the British Oxygen Company.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] As a guest of the SFA, Fabio Capello worked with manager Craig Brown and the team at Shawfield for a short stint in the early 1980s when he started coaching.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Relegation from the First Division in 1979–80 was followed by another promotion as Second Division champions in 1981–82.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Shawfield eventually came on the open market in 1983 with a £500,000 price tag.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club was served with a notice to quit Shawfield by 1986.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Alloa Athletic provided the final opposition at Shawfield on 28 April 1986.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The unpopular but necessary decision was taken to ground-share with city rivals Partick Thistle.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde spent five unhappy seasons at Firhill, and there was a sense of relief when Clyde departed.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club was grateful for the use of Firhill, but there was an underlying sense of being tolerated as an inconvenient annoyance.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 'Gypsy Army' reference came into being as Clyde supporters sought pride and solace during the club's homeless years.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club then negotiated a ground-share at Douglas Park with Hamilton Academical, where Clyde resided for two and a half seasons as plans were developed and implemented to build a new home in Cumbernauld.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Meanwhile, on the field, relegation from the First Division in 1990–91, was followed by promotion again as Second Division champions in 1992–93 and an immediate relegation in 1993–94.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, this continued the tradition of the yo-yo existence the club had become known for at certain times in previous decades.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Cumbernauld Development Corporation was keen to have a sports stadium and professional football team to promote the town, and Cumbernauld, with a 50,000+ population, seemed fertile ground on which to grow new support.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A new site called "Broadwood" was to have an integrated business, housing and leisure development with a football stadium at the heart of it.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] With the help of Football Trust backing, two modern stands began to emerge during the early 1990s.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Scottish League unusually granted permission for Clyde to switch grounds mid-season, and former landlords, Hamilton Academical, were the inaugural opposition on 5 February 1994.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A capacity crowd of 6000 watched as Clyde lost to the *Accies* 2–0.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde dropped to the third tier of football, and in 1998 they almost fell into the lowest reaches of Senior football.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, this was enough for the new chairman, Billy Carmichael, to introduce changes.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Ronnie MacDonald got appointed as manager, having worked at Maryhill Juniors.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] MacDonald signed a whole squad from the Junior ranks, and within two seasons Clyde had gained promotion.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Subsequently, Allan Maitland won promotion to the Scottish First Division in 1999.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 2003–04 season saw Clyde atop the League and looking set for the SPL.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] But Broadwood did not comply with SPL requirements and crucially Clyde was on the brink of being petitioned by their creditors and liquidated.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] While the chairman's fortune was well spent on players' wages, very little else got serviced.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The SPL relented and said Clyde could join them if the fourth stand got built.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] North Lanarkshire Council started the groundworks and then abruptly halted them as they became aware of Clyde's financial plight.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Plan B, playing at Kilmarnock, was investigated.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In the event, a draw with Ayr United and a home loss to Inverness Caledonian Thistle meant that Clyde missed out on promotion.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde Supporters' Trust formed during the 2003–04 season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Early that season some concerned fans met knowing that the chairman could not keep financing the Club indefinitely.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The timing of the Trust's formation coincided with Clyde's failure to gain promotion, and the chairman sought to sell his majority shareholding.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Following lengthy negotiations, a consortium of the Trust and traditional investors increased the majority shareholding for a nominal sum.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde Development Consortium took control of funds gathered by fans and investors and used it to finance the Club through a CVA to clear the debts.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In June 2005 the CVA was completed, and Clyde was mostly debt free.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Celtic were such heavy favourites that the game was presented as a gentle introduction for their new signing, Roy Keane.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The goal scorers for Clyde were Eddie Malone and Craig Bryson while Celtic's goal scorer was Maciej Zurawski.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde reached the 2006 Challenge Cup Final, their first final for 48 years, since their Scottish Cup success in 1958.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They lost the game 5–4 on a penalty shootout, after the game finished 1–1 following extra time.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Former Scotland captain Colin Hendry was appointed manager in summer 2007.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 14 August of that year, Clyde history was made when Michael Doherty became the youngest person ever to play for Clyde in a competitive match, a feat later broken by Connor Stevenson in a league match at Palmerston on 25 April 2009.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Hendry resigned in January 2008, due to family reasons.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Former Rangers defender John "Bomber" Brown replaced him as manager.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde entered the final game of the season needing to better Morton's result to avoid getting forced into the playoffs.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde won their game 3–0, but in a cruel twist of fate, Morton won their own game by the same scoreline, sending Clyde into a two-legged play-off with Second Division side Alloa Athletic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde lost the first leg 2–1 and at 3–1 down in the home second leg looked as good as relegated.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, a thrilling fightback saw Clyde level at 5–5 on aggregate (4–3 on the day) before adding another goal in extra time to progress.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Home and away victories over Airdrie United in the play-off final then secured First Division football at Broadwood for another season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, the following season Clyde finished bottom of the First Division and got relegated to the Second Division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Meanwhile, off the park, financial problems were once again apparent.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In a hope to try to avoid administration in June 2009, Clyde terminated the contracts of the entire first-team squad, with only youngsters remaining under contract at the club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The squad for 2009–10 was rebuilt on a drastically reduced budget with a repeat of open trials which were successful in 2005.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However early results were not good, and the board appointed Neil Watt as Director of Football and John McCormack as first team coach.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After a brief upturn in results, Clyde went six games without a win, and on Saturday 21 November, with the team sitting three points adrift at the bottom of the Second Division, it was announced that John Brown had left his position as manager.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On Monday, 5 April, John McCormack was sacked by Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] More history was made in a home match with Peterhead on 17 April 2010, when Willie Sawyers scored after only eight seconds, which became the fastest Clyde goal ever recorded.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Despite this, the club was subsequently relegated for a consecutive season, dropping down to the Third Division where they made a disastrous start to the campaign, including an 8–1 thrashing at the hands of Montrose.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On Wednesday 2 February 2011, Stuart Millar was sacked as manager of Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They finished 10th in the Third Division, which at 42nd and last place overall is the lowest position in the Scottish league system.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 20 April 2013, Clyde's owners voted to move to East Kilbride and rename the club EK Clyde FC, however, this plan would later be abandoned.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The 2013–14 season saw a significant improvement on the field when a League One play-off spot was secured in the penultimate league match of the season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In the previous six seasons Clyde had finished in the bottom two positions of every league campaign.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, the club missed out on promotion after a play-off semi-final defeat on penalties to East Fife.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Gordon Young became the first Clyde player to score with their first touch on their club debut in a match against Elgin City on 1 March 2014.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Duffy resigned as manager of Clyde on 19 May 2014 to take up the vacant managerial post at Greenock Morton, while John Taylor, a member of the boardroom since 1986, and the club's longest serving director had stepped down in April.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In October 2014, the club were declared officially debt free, having accumulated an unsustainable debt of £1.4 million as a result of the club's failed promotion bid to the SPL during season 2003–04, with the burden of debt having weighed heavily on the shoulders of the club for the next decade.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Scott Durie became the first Clyde player to play every single minute of every competitive match in a season, during the 2014–15 season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Former Rangers, Blackburn and Scotland midfielder Barry Ferguson was appointed as player-manager of Clyde in June 2014 and took the club to a 6th-place finish in his first season in charge.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Ferguson officially retired as a player towards the end of that season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The following year, Clyde finished 3rd in League Two but got beaten in the playoff final.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After nine years in the bottom tier of Scottish football, at the end of the 2018–19 season, Danny Lennon led Clyde to promotion to Scottish League One, beating Annan Athletic 2–1 on aggregate to win the promotion play-off final.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In April 2022, the club announced they would be leaving Broadwood at the end of the 2021–22 season, ending their 28-year stay in Cumbernauld.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They will be ground-sharing with Hamilton Academical at New Douglas Park from the start of the 2022–23 season, with a view of relocating to a new home back in Glasgow in the near future.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde's last match at Broadwood was a defeat by Airdrieonians on 23 April 2022.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde have had five home grounds since they formed in 1877.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The first of these was Barrowfield Park, situated on the banks of the River Clyde between the Glasgow neighbourhoods of Bridgeton and Dalmarnock.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] By 1898, Barrowfield became too small in capacity to deal with the large crowds of spectators.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club then moved across the river to build a new stadium, which would be known as Shawfield Stadium.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A crowd of 10,000 saw the first match at Shawfield against Celtic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In 1908, a group of 52,000 gathered for a game against Rangers, which remains Clyde's record home attendance to this day.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Financial pressures led to the club relinquishing ownership of the stadium in 1935, selling it to their former tenants, the Greyhound Racing Association.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] This arrangement continued satisfactorily for over 50 years until the GRA announced redevelopment plans for the stadium and gave Clyde notice to quit in 1986.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In 1990, Clyde had secured an agreement to move into a stadium in the new town of Cumbernauld, which due to shifting population patterns was by now one of the larger settlements in Scotland without a senior football team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The new all-seater Broadwood Stadium would not be ready until 1994.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde moved into the venue midway through the 1994–95 season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Broadwood has hosted Scotland U21 matches and four Scottish Challenge Cup finals in the past.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Broadwood was also home to Airdrieonians for four seasons from 1994 to 1998 and Rangers reserves for a while.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 9 December 2010, Clyde had informed their landlords at North Lanarkshire Council (NL Leisure) of their intention to relinquish their lease on Broadwood and move elsewhere.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Furthermore, on 19 October 2011, Clyde revealed that they were investigating the possibility of a move to East Kilbride, the largest town in Scotland without a senior football team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Another option was to move back to Rutherglen and develop the Clyde Gateway Stadium in a ground-sharing agreement.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] This had received approval from current tenants Rutherglen Glencairn.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After the Great War began, in September 1914, a fire completely destroyed the grandstand at Shawfield.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde were forced to switch their home games for a while.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Celtic, the club's East End neighbours, offered up Celtic Park as an alternative venue for home games.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After Celtic Park suffered similar damage in March 1929, they had to play the rest of their matches in the 1928–29 season at nearby Shawfield, thus reciprocating the earlier arrangement in 1914.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] On 1 March 1958 Clyde hosted Celtic in the Scottish Cup.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Set for Shawfield, the match was moved to Celtic Park over safety concerns.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, Clyde still had home advantage because the home stand tickets were initially reserved for Clyde ticket holders with Celtic tickets ineligible.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The *Bully Wee* won 2–0 in front of 65,000, with goals from Ring and Currie.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After quitting Shawfield in 1986, the club investigated several local options.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde secured an agreement with arch-rivals Partick Thistle to share their ground Firhill for five seasons until 1991.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Despite reaching an agreement to move into Broadwood in 1990, it would not be until 1994 when the ground was ready, so Clyde shared with Hamilton Accies at their Douglas Park stadium for a further three seasons.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club negotiated a groundshare with Alloa to use Recreation Park for the club's first home game of the 2012–13 season, a first round Challenge Cup match against Partick Thistle.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] During pre-season work had begun at Broadwood to replace the grass pitch with an artificial surface (astroturf) and the pitch was not finished in time for their first home match of the season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde were confident that the pitch would be completed and all the details finalised for the club's first home league match of the season in time for the visit of Peterhead.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The match was switched to Recreation Park for the second successive home game after a pitch inspection carried out earlier in the week by the SFL decided that the pitch was not at the stage of completion as expected.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Installation of the new surface was completed in time for the club's next home match of the league season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde Football Club is 100% owned by the supporters.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The supporters' fiercest rivalry is with Partick Thistle, given that the two clubs are both of smaller stature to that of Rangers and Celtic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, given the success of Partick Thistle and Clyde's relegation to Scottish League Two, such derby games have become a rarity in past years.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Both clubs were in League One together in the 2020–21 season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The number of years Clyde spent without a permanent home of their own led to the fans identifying themselves as the *Gypsy Army*.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde Supporters Social Club on Rutherglen Main Street burned down in the early 2000s and has never been rebuilt or re-opened.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] There was also a Supporters Club located in Kirkintilloch.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde Supporters' Trust was formed during season 2003–04.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A group of fans became aware of the club's severe financial problems as Billy Carmichael's reign as chairman came to an end.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It was formed in time to save the club and keep it in the supporter's hands in a time that coincided with Clyde's failure to gain promotion and the chairman looking to sell his majority shareholding.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] In the past the Supporters' Trust has financed the signings of players such as John Potter and Tom Brighton, and retaining the signatures of players such as Neil McGregor and David Hutton.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde supporters also run their own supporters team called Bully Wee United.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Bully Wee United are recognised as the official supporters team of Clyde and represent the club in the IFA League with matches well played Saturday mornings.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Matches are normally against the supporter's teams of the opposition facing the first team on the same day.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Bully Wee United is unique in most Scottish supporters teams as they operate a strict policy that only Clyde supporters may play for the team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Players must attend a minimum number of Clyde games over a season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde is also represented in the Scottish Central Amateur League by another supporters team named Broadwood Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They were crowned SSFL Division One league champions in 2005.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] They also won the SSFL League Cup in 2004 and SSFL Inter-Division Cup in 2003 making them the most successful Clyde supporters team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Broadwood Clyde play their homes games at Ravenswood in Cumbernauld on Sunday afternoons.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The ***Clyde View*** is Clyde's official matchday programme.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It won the Scottish Programme of the Year Award every season from 1995–96 to 2006–07, and again in 2008–09.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It also won the Scottish Divisional Programme of the Year Award every season from 1991–92 to 2011–12.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] It won the inaugural Scottish Divisional Programme Best Design of the Year Award for season 2011–12.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club's nickname, "The Bully Wee", is of uncertain origin although the club themselves have advanced three theories.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The first suggests that the clubs and supporters and perhaps players mainly came from Bridgeton, Glasgow, a tight working-class area whose inhabitants had a reputation as "wee bullies", with this becoming transposed as the Bully Wee.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Alternatively, it is also claimed that it comes from around 1900 when a group of French supporters paid a visit to Barrowfield and, upon the scoring of a disputed goal, were heard to remark "But il'y, oui?" or "Their goal, yes".
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Supporters heard this unfamiliar phrase as "Bully Wee", and the name stuck.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Clyde's supporters also go by the name of "Gypsy Army".
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Due to the number of years the club spent homeless, rival fans called Clyde fans "gypsies" as a slur.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The supporters of Clyde adopted this as a badge of honour and the "Gypsy Army" was born.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Historically seen as a Glasgow club, local rivalries (Glasgow derby) were developed and forged with other teams from in and around the city, in particular Celtic (also from the East End), Rangers, Partick Thistle and Queen's Park and the now-defunct Third Lanark.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] For most of the 20th century, they were six of leading clubs in the country.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] More often than not all six clubs resided in the top division, with fiercely contested competitions such as the Glasgow Cup and Glasgow Charity Cup (before European football) on top of national tournaments seeing the clubs pitted against one another multiple times a season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] A team called Thistle FC, also known Glasgow or Bridgeton Thistle, were early rivals to the club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Formed a decade before Clyde in 1868, Thistle's first ground was situated nearby at the club's original home Barrowfield Park.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Thistle's last fixture was a friendly against the full first team of Clyde at Barrowfield before going out of existence in 1894.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The Clyde vs Partick Thistle derby was previously a fierce battle between two of Glasgow's smaller clubs, in comparison to the Old Firm.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The rivalry intensified when Thistle became Clyde's landlords at Firhill for five years in the 1980s.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The decision to groundshare was never fully accepted by either set of fans.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] After quitting Clyde on free transfer to sign for the Firhill club (newly promoted to the SPL) in 2002, Jamie Mitchell stated he was shocked by the reaction of Clyde supporters to the move.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] He referred to it as getting the "Mo Johnston treatment".
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Former *Jags* midfielder Scott Chaplain (once a signing target for Clyde) spoke of the "competitive edges to those particular matches" after playing in the fixtures many times.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] When talking about a possible groundshare again, Partick Thistle chairman David Beattie said it would reignite the Glasgow-rivalry saying "the healthy rivalry between ourselves and the Bully Wee is historical".
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Due to Partick Thistle's promotion to Scotland's highest professional league, the Scottish Premiership, in the 2010s and Clyde's relegations to the lower leagues in the same period, matches between the two clubs became less common.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] However, by 2020 they found themselves in the same division (Scottish League One) once again, with a revived version of the Glasgow Cup also offering more meetings.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] During the 2010s, Queen's Park became the natural rivals to Clyde, as both clubs were stuck in the bottom league (fourth tier) for the majority of the decade.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] From 2010 to 2016, Clyde were on a demoralising run of results against Queen's Park: the *Spiders* won 17 and drew 3 of the 26 matches.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] This included a run of 11 successive wins (scoring 29 goals in that run).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Geographically classed as a North Lanarkshire club since the 1994 move to Cumbernauld, Clyde's matches against Airdrieonians, Albion Rovers, Motherwell or Hamilton Academical can be considered a Lanarkshire derby.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] The club has appointed 35 permanent managers in its history, with one repeat appointment.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p01] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Clyde put together a reserve team for the SFL's Reserve League Cup competition, which included a mixture of first team fringe players and youngsters.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club won the Reserve League Cup for the first time in May 2008.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They defeated Livingston 4–1 on their own ground at Almondvale with Dave McKay scoring all four goals for Clyde.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It was the team's first piece of silverware at reserve level for twenty years.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The following season the club were knocked out by Ross County in the semi-finals losing 3–0 in Dingwall.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It was common from the beginning of reserve football for the majority of club's reserve teams (second XI's) to go by the tag ‘A’ or sometimes ‘B’ or even ‘C’ if a club had more than one reserve side.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It wasn't until after the formation of the new Scottish Reserve League in 1955 that today's reserve teams went by the actual tag ‘reserves’ and have done since 1957.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] During the 1881–82 season, Clyde reached the semi-finals of the Scottish 2nd XI Cup in the competitions the first season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] In 1896–97 they reached their first 'major' cup final, the Scottish 2nd XI Cup final eventually losing 4–0 to Hearts.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] After reaching the semi-finals again in 1905–06, they were thwarted by arch-rivals Partick Thistle this time.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club first joined the Scottish Reserve League in 1909–10 and found the first few years of competing in the league tough.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It wasn't until the 1913–14 season when they made their mark when they lost 1–0 at Hearts in a league decider for the Reserve League title.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It meant that the club missed out on a unique League and Cup double after they captured the Scottish 2nd XI Cup for the first time that season.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They dispatched of St Mirren in the final over two legs (1–1 away and 3–1 at home).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They successfully defended the Scottish 2nd XI Cup the following season when Clyde overcame Falkirk in the final over two legs (2–1 loss away and a 3–1 home win).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Their third and final Scottish 2nd XI Cup triumph came in 1941–42.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It would be the team's last 'major' cup success for the next sixty-six years.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] In 1945–46 they reached their last Scottish 2nd XI Cup final losing to Hibs, after a superb 6–2 derby victory over arch-rivals Partick Thistle in the semi-finals.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Scottish Reserve League merged with the Scottish C Division (third tier) for the 1949–50 season creating two regionalised divisions (South/West and North/East) with Clyde entering a reserve team in the South & West region.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club was crowned champions in 1949–50 and they retained their title in 1950–51.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Despite successive titles, there was no promotion as only first teams could gain promotion to Division B.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] As reserve teams got excluded from the Scottish League Cup, the C Division had their League Cup.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Clyde couldn't quite match the success in the cup that they had in the league as they never won the competition.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The best they could manage were semi-final appearances in 1951–52 and in 1953–54.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] After both regional C Divisions got scrapped in June 1955, a new Scottish Reserve League started up.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The new Reserve League was an exclusively all First Division league (a mirror image of the senior league) and all Second Division clubs' reserve sides got excluded from joining.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] There were several seasons when not all clubs took part.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] As for teams who were turned away or excluded from joining, they joined various supplementary leagues over the next few years.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] For the first few seasons between 1955 and 1960, Clyde regularly finished quite high up the table or at least in a mid-table position.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] From then onwards in the seasons they spent in the league, the team were often at the wrong end of the table.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] In one of the seasons that Clyde didn't participate in the Reserve League, they joined the Combined Reserve League for a single season in 1961–62.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Due to the small number of teams involved, the competition got split into an Autumn Series and Spring Series.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club won the Autumn Series and finished second overall in the Combined Table.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Just like Clyde's first team, whose last spell in the Scottish top flight came in 1974–75, the same fate happened to their reserve team following a further league restructure at senior and reserve level.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Reserve League set-up changed again in 1975 after a reorganisation of the 'senior' Scottish League into Premier-First-Second Divisions.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The new Premier Reserve League was a mirror image of the new Scottish Premier Division in terms of membership.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Lower league clubs used varying set-ups such as east–west sections and midweek competitions.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] In later games, clubs didn't always participate as running a reserve side became expensive.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] It wasn't until season 1979–80 when Clyde gained membership to re-enter a reserve team in the Scottish Reserve League.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They got placed in the regional West division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Finishing bottom in their first season, it was a further two seasons before they returned.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They fared much better during the 1987–88 season when they won the division.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Season 2000–01 was Clyde's last in the West Reserves League eventually before all reserves leagues got scrapped after season 2007–08.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club ran youth teams at under-20, under-17, under-15, under-14, under-13, under-12, and under-11 level.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] There was an under-18 team until 2003, when it made way for under-17 and under-19 teams.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The under-20 team replaced the under-19 team in 2014.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club also ran Football Schools in Cumbernauld (since 2006) and Glasgow Southside (since 2008).
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Both schools have since been awarded the SFA Quality Mark Award at Standard Level and then at Development Level.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Community Foundation received the Gold award in the SFA Quality Mark category for grassroots football.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Foundation also received the Young Start Award in 2017 to run a project called *Start Young, Grow Young*.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club were forced to scrap their youth academy from under 11 to under 17 levels in 2015 citing a reduction in funding from the Scottish FA, with the under-20 side the only youth team remaining, which acts as a feeder to the first team for young players.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The team reached the Scottish Youth Cup semi finals in 1988, but were beaten by Dunfermline Athletic.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The under-17 team reached the SFL Youth Cup final in 2004 losing 4–1 on penalties to Hamilton Accies at New Douglas Park despite scoring in stoppage time of extra time to make it 1–1.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Both of the under-19 and under-17 teams reached the semi-finals of their SFL Youth Cups in 2006.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The under-19 team finished runners-up behind Celtic in the inaugural SPFL under-19 league in 2014.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The under-19 team travelled to the Netherlands in 2003, taking part in a highly rated youth football programme called the *Leonardo Project* hosted by FC Dordrecht.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They played three times against an under-19 team of the hosts, which contained Dutch youth internationalists, winning two and drawing one.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] In the third match, the opposition was made up of reserves and first team fringe players.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] They followed this up with a win over local amateur team vv Capelle and a narrow defeat to a youthful FC Utrecht team.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Lanarkshire FA started the Lanarkshire Supercounty Trophy for all four senior Lanarkshire clubs' under-17 teams in 2013.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Clyde beat Motherwell in the semi-final, but lost to Accies in the final.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The under-17's also reached their sectional League Cup final in 2017.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Community Foundation youth teams reached Divisional Cup finals in 2018 and 2019.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Scottish internationals Pat Nevin, Steve Archibald and Ian Ferguson also came through the Clyde youth system.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The club launched its official Hall of Fame in 2011, with five inaugural inductees.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] The Clyde team of season 1966–67 was inducted in 2014.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] There is also a Hall of Fame section on the club website.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] A list of fully international capped players while they played for the club.
[src:alfred-holt/clyde-f-c-p02] Players are alphabetically ordered by nationality, forenames, and lastly surnames.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] A **compound steam engine** unit is a type of steam engine where steam is expanded in two or more stages.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] A typical arrangement for a compound engine is that the steam is first expanded in a high-pressure (HP) cylinder, then having given up heat and losing pressure, it exhausts directly into one or more larger-volume low-pressure (LP) cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Multiple-expansion engines employ additional cylinders, of progressively lower pressure, to extract further energy from the steam.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Invented in 1781, this technique was first employed on a Cornish beam engine in 1804.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Around 1850, compound engines were introduced into Lancashire textile mills.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In a single-expansion (or 'simple') steam engine, the high-pressure steam enters the cylinder at boiler pressure through an inlet valve.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The steam pressure forces the piston down the cylinder, until the valve shuts (e.g. after 25% of the piston's stroke).
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] After the steam supply is cut off the trapped steam continues to expand, pushing the piston to the end of its stroke, where the exhaust valve opens and expels the partially depleted steam to the atmosphere, or to a condenser.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] This "cut-off" allows much more work to be extracted, since the expansion of the steam is doing additional work beyond that done by the steam at boiler pressure.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] An earlier cut-off increases the expansion ratio, which in principle allows more energy to be extracted and increases efficiency.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Ideally, the steam would expand adiabatically, and the temperature would drop corresponding to the volume increase.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] However, in practice the material of the surrounding cylinder acts as a heat reservoir, cooling the steam in the earlier part of the expansion and heating it in the later part.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] These irreversible heat flows decrease the efficiency of the process, so that, beyond a certain point, further increasing the expansion ratio would actually decrease efficiency, in addition to decreasing the mean effective pressure and thus the power of the engine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] A solution to the dilemma was invented in 1804 by British engineer Arthur Woolf, who patented his *Woolf high pressure compound engine* in 1805.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In the compound engine, high-pressure steam from the boiler first expands in a high-pressure (HP) cylinder and then enters one or more subsequent lower pressure (LP) cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The complete expansion of the steam occurs across multiple cylinders and, as there is less expansion in each cylinder, the steam cools less in each cylinder, making higher expansion ratios practical and increasing the efficiency of the engine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] There are other advantages: as the temperature range is smaller, cylinder condensation is reduced.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Loss due to condensation is restricted to the LP cylinder.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Pressure difference is less in each cylinder so there is less steam leakage at the piston and valves.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The turning moment is more uniform, so balancing is easier and a smaller flywheel may be used.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Only the smaller HP cylinder needs to be built to withstand the highest pressure, which reduces the overall weight.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Similarly, components are subject to less strain, so they can be lighter.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The reciprocating parts of the engine are lighter, reducing the engine vibrations.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The compound could be started at any point in the cycle, and in the event of mechanical failure the compound could be reset to act as a simple, and thus keep running.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] To derive equal work from lower-pressure steam requires a larger cylinder volume as this steam occupies a greater volume.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Therefore, the bore, and in rare cases the stroke as well, are increased in low-pressure cylinders, resulting in larger cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Double-expansion (usually just known as 'compound') engines expand the steam in two stages, but this does not imply that all such engines have two cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The adoption of compounding was widespread for stationary industrial units where the need was for increased power at decreasing cost, and almost universal for marine engines after 1880.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] It was not widely used in railway locomotives where it was often perceived as complicated and unsuitable for the harsh railway operating environment and limited space afforded by the loading gauge (particularly in Britain).
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Compounding was never common on British railways and not employed at all after 1930, but was used in a limited way in many other countries.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] It is a logical extension of the compound engine (described above) to split the expansion into yet more stages to increase efficiency.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The result is the **multiple-expansion engine**.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Such engines use either three or four expansion stages and are known as *triple-* and *quadruple-expansion engines* respectively.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] These engines use a series of double-acting cylinders of progressively increasing diameter and/or stroke and hence volume.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] These cylinders are designed to divide the work into three or four equal portions, one for each expansion stage.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The adjacent image shows an animation of a triple-expansion engine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The steam travels through the engine from left to right.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The valve chest for each of the cylinders is to the left of the corresponding cylinder.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Though the first mills were driven by water power, once steam engines were adopted the manufacturer no longer needed to site the mills by running water.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Cotton spinning required ever larger mills to fulfil the demand, and this drove the owners to demand increasingly powerful engines.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] When boiler pressure had exceeded 60 psi, compound engines achieved a thermo-dynamic advantage, but it was the mechanical advantages of the smoother stroke that was the deciding factor in the adoption of compounds.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In 1859, there was 75,886 ihp (indicated horsepower) of engines in mills in the Manchester area, of which 32,282 ihp was provided by compounds though only 41,189 ihp was generated from boilers operated at over 60psi.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] To generalise, between 1860 and 1926 all Lancashire mills were driven by compounds.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The last compound built was by Buckley and Taylor for Wye No.2 mill, Shaw.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] This engine was a cross-compound design to 2,500 ihp, driving a 24 ft, 90 ton flywheel, and operated until 1965.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In the marine environment, the general requirement was for autonomy and increased operating range, as ships had to carry their coal supplies.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The old salt-water boiler was thus no longer adequate and had to be replaced by a closed fresh-water circuit with condenser.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The result from 1880 onwards was the **multiple-expansion engine** using three or four expansion stages (*triple-* and *quadruple-expansion engines*).
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] These engines used a series of double-acting cylinders of progressively increasing diameter and/or stroke (and hence volume) designed to divide the work into three or four, as appropriate, equal portions for each expansion stage.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Where space is at a premium, two smaller cylinders of a large sum volume might be used for the low-pressure stage.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Multiple-expansion engines typically had the cylinders arranged in-line, but various other formations were used.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In the late 19th century, the Yarrow–Schlick–Tweedy balancing 'system' was used on some marine triple-expansion engines.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Y–S–T engines divided the low-pressure expansion stages between two cylinders, one at each end of the engine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] This allowed the crankshaft to be better balanced, resulting in a smoother, faster-responding engine which ran with less vibration.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] This made the 4-cylinder triple-expansion engine popular with large passenger liners (such as the *Olympic* class), but was ultimately replaced by the virtually vibration-free steam turbine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The development of this type of engine was important for its use in steamships as by exhausting to a condenser the water could be reclaimed to feed the boiler, which was unable to use seawater.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Land-based steam engines could simply exhaust much of their steam, as feed water was usually readily available.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Prior to and during World War II, the expansion engine dominated marine applications where high vessel speed was not essential.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] It was superseded by the steam turbine when speed was required, such as for warships and ocean liners.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] HMS *Dreadnought* of 1905 was the first major warship to replace the proven technology of the reciprocating engine with the then-novel steam turbine.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] While designs for compound locomotives may date as far back as James Samuel's 1856 patent for a "continuous expansion locomotive", the practical history of railway compounding begins with Anatole Mallet's designs in the 1870s.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Mallet locomotives were operated in the United States up to the end of mainline steam by the Norfolk and Western Railway.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The designs of Alfred George de Glehn in France also saw significant use, especially in the rebuilds of André Chapelon.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] A wide variety of compound designs were tried around 1900, but most were short-lived in popularity, due to their complexity and maintenance liability.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] In the 20th century the superheater was widely adopted, and the vast majority of steam locomotives were simple-expansion (with some compound locomotives converted to simple).
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] It was realised by engineers that locomotives at steady speed were worked most efficiently with a wide-open regulator and early cut-off, the latter being set via the reversing gear.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] A locomotive operating at very early cut-off of steam (e.g. at 15% of the piston stroke) allows maximum expansion of the steam, with less wasted energy at the end of the stroke.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Superheating eliminates the condensation and rapid loss of pressure that would otherwise occur with such expansion.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Large American locomotives used two cross-compound steam-driven air compressors, e.g. the Westinghouse 8 1/2" 150-D, for the train brakes.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The presentation follows Sommerfeld's textbook, which contains a diagram (Figure 17) that is not reproduced for copyright reasons.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Consider a four-cylinder engine on a ship.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Let *x* be the vertical direction, *z* be the fore–aft direction, and *y* be the port–starboard direction.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Let the four cylinders be mounted in a row along the *z* axis, so that their pistons are pointed downwards.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The pistons are connected to the same crankshaft via long vertical rods.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Now, as the engine operates, the vertical position of cylinder i is equal to $x_{i}$ .
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] As each cylinder moves up and down, it exerts a vertical force on its mounting frame equaling $M_{i}{\ddot {x}}_{i}$ .
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The YST system aims to make sure that the total of all four forces cancels out as exactly as possible.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] This gives us eight equations to solve, which is in general possible if there are at least eight variables of the system that we can vary.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Of the variables of the system, $M_{i},r_{i}$ are fixed by the design of the cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] Also, the absolute values of $a_{2},a_{3},a_{4}$ do not matter, only their ratios matter.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The YST system requires at least four cylinders.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] With three cylinders, the same derivation gives us only six variables to vary, which is insufficient to solve all eight equations.
[src:alfred-holt/compound-steam-engine] The YST system is used on ships such as the SS Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse and SS Deutschland (1900).
